title: For Sale/Trade:  .375 H&H Mag. Remington 700 Custom Shop 1969 model
postcontent:
Price $1500.00 -OBO- 
This rifle was a special order model from the Custom Shop in 1969. This is a very rare rifle. You can be sure your friend will never show up to the hunt with one of these, and given the quality and collectability of this firearm, they wont show up with a rifle nearly as nice as your's. The stock has rosewood on the grip and end caps. The bolt is jeweled. It has a 26" Bull barrel. The action is one of the smothest actions I have ever felt and the trigger breaks like glass at about 2lbs. The barrel is drilled and tapped for safarie sights but the rifle is set up with a variable 2x7 Leupold scope. This rifle is all original, even the buttstock pad. You will not find this rifle in better condition. If you are reading this you allready know how powerfull the .375 H&H Magnum round is. This is the prefered round for African big game hunts. It is a massave, powerfull and flat shooting round. The only reason I am considering letting this go is I am not planning any big game hunts any time soon. I have taken an intrest in long range shooting compitions. I would be open to trades for .338 lapua rifles or other tactical firearms. I will also consider reasonable cash offers. Must have Ohio ID. Email, Call or Text REDACTED. 
Thank you for your interest,
Alex

Note- There have been some questions. No, this is not the BDL model. Remington did not offer the big bore calabers from the factory in 1969. They had to be ordered from the custom shop. Note the rosewood and barrel. It is a "C Grade" custom, meaning there is no engraving. The custom shop's grading system starts at C, then moves on to D and E. These levels are determined by the ammount of engraving you order. The quality of firearm put out at that time this rifle was made is superior to what you would get today with their current models that cost over to 4k. Please let me know if you have any other questions.

**Update**
I am moving soon so I am interested in liquidating some of my things, more money for my move and less things to cart with me. Because of this, I am throwing in a full 20rd box of Federal ammo valued at $55. Also do not be shy to make me an offer. I am prepared to negotiate in order to make the price work for both of us. I am a reasonable guy, that want to sell a very nice rifle, so no reasonable offer will be turned away.

title: Want To Buy:  A better way to pay for guns
postcontent:
I've used armslist alot. If there was a record of transactions like on gunbroker, I'd have a pretty good seller feedback, and buyer too. But recently, I succumbed to a scam, one that almost got me on armslist ($800 kimber gold cup), and succeeded in getting a friend of mine. I avoided that scam, but did get caught with one involving texas gun traders, and a google voice phone number, that only received texts (suspicious? yes.) 

Im not a paid sponsor, nor am I in any way affiliated with them, but after these events I've chosen to spread the word about pistolpay.com The website is just starting out, but if people support it, and use it, then scams like this wont happen to any gun buyer again.

location: Russian GP-5 Gas Mask, Denver, Colorado
postcontent:
Complete set of a Cold War era Gas mask that the Soviet Union would issue to civilians. Mask includes carrying case, hose, and "coffee can" filter. 

These masks are labeled on sizes from 0-5, This one is a 1 so it is a Small. However, it is made of latex and was able to fit it around a basketball. Still provides a tight seal, and everything is functional.

Despite rumors of these filters being dangerous, they are not. If you cut one open you will only find activated charcoal and a cotton filter/liner.
